# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The **10th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1807, to March 4, 1809, during the seventh and eighth years of Thomas Jefferson's presidency.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 census; both chambers had an overwhelming Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, and 1 interim appointment.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 4 resignations, 4 deaths, and 2 vacancies from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Democratic-Republicans had no net change and Federalists picked up 2 seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/10th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Elections to the United States House of Representatives were held in Pennsylvania on Tuesday, October 11, 1791, for the 2nd Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Six Pro-Administration and two Anti-Administration Representatives had been elected on an at-large basis in the previous election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The elections in Pennsylvania were the last elections held for the 2nd Congress, out of the states that were in the Union at the start of the Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The previous election had been held at-large, but for the 2nd Congress, Pennsylvania divided itself up into 8 districts.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Note: Many of these counties covered much larger areas in 1791 than they do today, having since been divided into smaller counties.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Five incumbents (3 Anti-Administration and 2 Pro-Administration) ran for re-election, four of whom won.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The incumbents George Clymer (P) and Henry Wynkoop (P) of the 2nd district and Thomas Scott (P) of the 8th district did not run for re-election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Muhlenberg switched from Pro-Administration to Anti-Administration.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Four Pro-Administration and four Anti-Administration candidates were elected, a net gain of 2 seats for the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Election data are incomplete for the 1st and 2nd districts and are missing for the 4th and 5th districts.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on October 9, 1792, for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Eight representatives, 4 Pro-Administration and 4 Anti-Administration, had been elected in the previous election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] In the previous election, Pennsylvania had been divided into 8 districts.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Five additional seats had been apportioned to Pennsylvania after the 1790 census.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] All 13 seats were elected at-large, an attempt by the Pro-Administration-majority legislature of Pennsylvania to prevent the election of Anti-Administration Representatives.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This backfired and an 8-5 Anti-Administration majority was elected.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was the last year in which Pennsylvania would elect all of its representatives at-large.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] In the following election, Pennsylvania would be divided up into 12 districts (including one plural district).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] At various times between 1873 and 1945, between 1 and 4 of Pennsylvania's Representatives were elected at-large, with the rest being elected from single-member districts.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1806–07 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 29, 1806 (in New York) and August 4, 1807 (in Tennessee).
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 10th United States Congress convened on October 26, 1807.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They occurred during Thomas Jefferson's second term.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 142 seats, representing 17 states.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Democratic-Republicans continued to build on their huge supermajority.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were actually able to take over two more seats than they had in the previous Congress, which they controlled by a margin of better than three to one.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Commitment to agrarian policy allowed the Democratic-Republicans to dominate rural districts, which represented the bulk of the nation.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the other hand, supporters of the Federalists, even in their traditional base of support in the urban centers of coastal New England, continued to lament the ineffectiveness of their party and its lack of electoral appeal.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With a net change of 2 seats between the two parties, this was the smallest net change in US history in the House of Representatives until 2024.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1806 and 1807 during the 9th United States Congress and 10th United States Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by date then district.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected its members on September 15, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware elected its member October 7, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia elected its members October 6, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky elected its members August 4, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland elected its members October 6, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts elected its members November 3, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire elected its members August 25, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Jersey elected its members October 14–15, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists ran a mixed ticket consisting of 2 Federalists (Aaron Ogden and John Beatty) and 4 Democratic-Republicans (William Helms, Ebenezer Elmer, George Maxwell, and Adam Boyd), one of whom (William Helms) was also on the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists capitalized on resentment over the replacement on the official Democratic-Republican ticket of Ebenezer Elmer, from South Jersey, with Thomas Newbold from Monmouth County and the retention of James Sloan.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This ticket was formed too late to gain sufficient support, but the Federalists did do much better in state elections that year than they had in previous elections.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York elected representatives to the 10th Congress on April 29 – May 1, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the second and last election in which Districts 2 and 3 were elected on a joint ticket.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York redistricted in the next election.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina elected its members August 15, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Ohio elected its member October 14, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Both candidates were Democratic-Republicans, but from election articles published in The Scioto Gazette it was suggested that James Pritchard was the candidate of the Ohio Quids and that in a few counties, notably Columbiana and Jefferson, he was also supported by the Federalists.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania elected its members October 14, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island elected its members August 26, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island law required a majority of votes to win.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this election, only one candidate won a majority on the first ballot, and so a run-off election was required to choose the second seat.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina elected its members October 13–14, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Tennessee elected its members August 3–4, 1807, after the Congress began but before the first session met.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont elected its members September 2, 1806.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia elected its members in April 1807, after the Congress began but before the first session met.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the previous congress, there were three territories with non-voting delegates in the 10th Congress.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Indiana Territory, the legislature elected the delegate.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The source used did not have information about Mississippi or Orleans Territory.
[src:1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1806-07-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Mississippi used popular election in 1808, while Orleans Territory elected its delegate by the legislature in 1808, suggesting Orleans probably used legislative election this year, too.
